                <details class="py-3">
                  <summary
                    class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800 text-sm"
                      >Why do some datasheets quote kgf·m instead of N·m?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">&#9662;</span>
                  </summary>
                  <div class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Kilogram-force metre (kgf·m) is a legacy unit based on
                    gravitational force. Although SI recommends using N·m, kgf·m
                    is still encountered in older drawings, Asian equipment and
                    some translated manuals. This converter helps you translate
                    those values into N·m and other modern units.
                  </div>
                </details>

                <details class="py-3">
                  <summary
                    class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800 text-sm"
                      >Is N·m the same as joule (J)?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">&#9662;</span>
                  </summary>
                  <div class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Dimensionally, both N·m and J can be expressed as kg·m²/s²,
                    but in engineering practice they represent different
                    quantities: N·m is used for torque (a vector moment), while
                    J is used for energy and work. For clarity, always write
                    torque in N·m and energy in J, even though the units are
                    dimensionally equivalent.
                  </div>
                </details>

                <details class="py-3">
                  <summary
                    class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800 text-sm"
                      >How many in·lb are in 1 ft·lb?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">&#9662;</span>
                  </summary>
                  <div class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    1 ft·lb equals 12 in·lb, because 1 foot = 12 inches and the
                    same pound-force is assumed in both units. The converter
                    automatically uses this ratio to ensure consistency between
                    ft·lb and in·lb values.
                  </div>
                </details>

